<HL>
   Program Trading Volume
   Rose on Big Board in Week
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Program trading accounted for an average of
9.6% of New York Stock Exchange volume, or 16 million shares
a day, in the week ended July 20.
   That was up from 7.9% the previous week, the Big Board
said in its weekly report on the computer-aided trading
strategies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The most active program traders for the week were Morgan
Stanley Group Inc. (17.4 million shares), General Electric
Co.'s Kidder, Peabody Group Inc. (10.8 million shares),
Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. (7.1 million shares), Susquehanna
Investment Group (6.1 million shares) and First Boston Corp.,
a subsidairy of CS First Boston Inc. (5.5 million shares).
These five firms accounted for 58% of all program trading on
the exchange.
   Program trading is the purchase or sale of a group of at
least 15 and often hundreds of different stocks. Stock-index
arbitrage, which involves stock purchases and sales with
offsetting trades in futures and options, was led by Kidder
Peabody, which accounted for 32% of the total.
</TEXT>
