<HL>
   Free to Enjoy the Cruelty of the Streets
   ----
   By J. Douglas Ousley
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<LP>
   When a church opens its doors for worship, it opens them
to everyone, and that should include the homeless, no matter
their physical or mental condition. But this Christian
response can also be dangerous -- witness last year's
horrifying murder of a worshipper in St. Patrick's Cathedral
by a deranged homeless man.
   At the church where I am rector, a midtown Manhattan
Episcopal parish, just such people -- homeless and
unmistakably very mentally ill -- do sometimes wander in
during our Sunday services. One man in particular, swathed in
torn and dirty clothes and unable to speak coherently, has
come in several times; he walks quickly up a side aisle,
enters a pew near the front, kneels and seems to pray, though
it be only babbling.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   He even came in briefly while the new Episcopal bishop of
New York was conducting confirmation ceremonies. As on
previous occasions, he knelt, seemed to pray, then jumped up
and walked out down the center aisle, speaking frantically
but causing only minimal disturbance.
   But on a recent Sunday, his pattern changed radically. As
my associate minister was giving her sermon, the man came
quickly up the center aisle in a very agitated state. He
entered a front pew, knelt and then stared at the woman in
the pulpit. Suddenly, he scrambled from the pew and ran
toward her, shouting.
   My associate stopped speaking but held her ground in the
pulpit. Fortunately, two laymen reacted quickly and ran up to
either side of the man, touched his arms gently and quietly
persuaded him to leave. They escorted him back down the
center aisle as he raged and shouted.
   "And we will pray for him, too," my associate told the
congregation.
   Though only a brief intrusion, it left us all a bit
shaken, realizing how differently and violently such an
incident might have ended. And, of course, thoughts of our
own safety aside, we are concerned for the hundreds of people
such as our anguished visitor who are living on the city's
streets, most of them seemingly mentally ill. Our church,
like so many in the city, has programs to aid the homeless.
But our concern also leads us to a philosophical, legal and,
sometimes, religious debate with ourselves: Should insane
people who roam the streets be confined against their will or
should they be allowed to remain free?
   Many are on the streets as a result of the closing of
mental institutions in the 1960s and '70s. Critics who
campaigned against these institutions said they were more
barbaric prisons than hospitals for healing; sadly, the
community-based outpatient clinics that were supposed to have
replaced them have never materialized.
   When I began my ministry in New York City in the early
1970s, I, too, argued that these unfortunates were better off
on the street than in some hellish asylum. Now, I am not so
sure.
   A friend who is both a professor of philosophy and an
Episcopal priest doesn't accept the position that society's
overriding concern is for the freedom of movement of the
insane. "I am a member of the American Civil Liberties Union
and I am a Christian," he told me. "The ACLU part of me says
they should not be locked up; the Christian part of me says
that it is not right to let them roam the streets in such
terrible shape."
   My friend's statement of the alternatives shows that it's
not simply a question of confining the disturbed against
their will or letting them live free -- for what does "free"
mean in such cases? How could the man who lunged toward the
pulpit in our church be described as exercising his free will
if he is clearly unaware of what he is doing? How could he be
said to have civil rights that include freedom of movement if
his actions are driven by inner compulsions over which he has
no control?
   Surely not only the Christian would take a larger view
that leaving the man in a degraded state not only doesn't
help him but casts a moral shadow over the society that is
guaranteeing him his putative freedom of movement. Surely not
only the Christian would wonder if we would all be better off
if the man were confined and had a better chance for a more
human existence.
   We need, then, to recognize that confining at least some
of the mentally ill may be the best thing for them -- not
just pragmatically, for the good of society, but in humanist
and spiritual terms, for their own good. Already, in New York
City at least, there appears to be wide public sympathy for
measures to keep the homeless from bus and train stations. As
these measures could reflect a coming wave of resentment of
the homeless themselves, it may be time to find ways to get
the mentally ill homeless off the streets.
   As for those who are not insane but who are in danger of
being committed by unscupulous relatives, their rights can be
safeguarded, while those who clearly cannot care for
themselves are cared for. While the indigency of the street
people should make us careful about sweeping them out of
sight for our convenience, we can maintain institutions for
the mentally ill in humane and dignified ways rather than
allowing the least of these, our brothers and sisters, to
suffer the effects of their alleged freedom.
   ---
   Mr. Ousley is rector of the Church of the Incarnation in
New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0104
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900803-0104.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   House Votes to Let Airports Charge
   Passengers Up to $3 Departure Tax
   ----
   By Laurie McGinley
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House voted to let airports slap
departure taxes of up to $3 on passengers, but the Senate may
ground the proposal.
   The House bill would let the nation's 71 largest airports
impose the fees to pay for airport expansion and noise
reduction. There would be a limit of two charges per one-way
trip, but a passenger could end up paying as much as $12 on a
round trip with intermediate stops.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   After a contentious debate, the House, by a 252-171 vote,
rebuffed a bid by Rep. Doug Bosco (D., Calif.) to delete the
provision permitting the taxes.
   "Airline passengers are once again on the verge of being
taken for a ride by the White House," said Rep. Norman Mineta
(D., Calif.), an opponent of the fees, officially dubbed
passenger facilities charges. "The Congress shouldn't license
this slap at the consumer." He said the government should
first spend the $8 billion surplus in the aviation trust
fund, which is financed by the 8% airline ticket tax.
   But Glenn Anderson (D., Calif.), chairman of the House
Public Works and Transportation Committee, argued that the
new fees are needed to augment the spending.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner has made approval
of the fees a top priority, and that was reflected in the
vote on the Bosco amendment. Republicans voted overwhelmingly
against the amendment, while Democrats were split.
   Still pending before Congress is a Bush administration
proposal to increase the airline ticket tax to 10% from 8%.
That proposal is expected to be adopted as part of the budget
negotiations.
   The House bill also authorizes $17.7 billion in spending
by the Federal Aviation Administration on airport development
and air-traffic control programs for the next two years. The
final vote on the bill was 405-15.
   In the Senate, prospects for the legislation are murky.
Sen. Ernest Hollings (D., S.C.), chairman of the Commerce
Committee, and Sen. Wendell Ford, (D., Ky.), chairman of the
aviation subcommittee, oppose the passenger facilities
charges. According to their aides, the senators don't plan to
pass an FAA authorization bill this year because they don't
want to provide a vehicle for the departure-tax provision.
The agency would receive funding in any case.
   Congress banned departure taxes in the early 1970s because
some local governments were using the money for non-airport
projects -- a practice prohibited under the new House bill.
Airports levying departure taxes would be required to
relinquish up to half of their regular federal funding. Most
of the unused federal funds would go to a discretionary fund
for smaller airports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0103
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900803-0103.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Washington Wire:
   A Special Weekly Report From
   The Wall Street Journal's
   Capital Bureau
   ----
   Compiled by Ronald G. Shafer
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST TAXES LABOR FREST
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
</GV>
<LP>
   IRAQ'S ATTACK on Kuwait rouses demands to temper U.S.
defense cuts.
   The invasion is bound to help Bush's efforts to stave off
some reductions. The Navy is more likely to get funds for
fast military cargo ships. Some aircraft and non-nuclear
missile programs also should benefit from the Mideast
tension. Bush can use the crisis to argue that lawmakers
should consider "what could happen 10 years from now," says
former defense chief Harold Brown.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Backers of the B-2 use Iraqi dangers to renew their push
to save the bomber. But critics argue that such programs were
meant to deter Soviet nuclear threats, not deal with Third
World blow-ups. House Democrats say their proposed cuts spare
conventional weapons, such as fighter jets, that are most
useful in regional crises.
   Big cuts are still likely, but the crisis changes the
mood. Sen. Dole calls it a "wake-up call" for a strong
defense.
                                                                                                       

   ISRAEL REAPS immediate political benefit from the Iraqi
invasion.
   "Saddam Hussein replaces the Ayatollah as the devil
incarnate in the Mideast, and Israel's strategic importance
is again highlighted," says New York Rep. Downey. The Iraqi
dictator's aggression is sure to shore up political support
for U.S. aid to Israel. The split among Arab nations also is
seen as an opportunity for Israel to face up to long-term
problems in the Mideast.
   "Israel can't afford to have the Saudis under the gun and
neither can the Arab world," says Wisconsin Rep. Obey,
chairman of a House panel overseeing foreign aid. But chances
for pressuring the Israeli government to accept Baker's
Mideast peace plan evaporate as the the Iraqi attack
strengthens Israel's political standing in the U.S.
                                                                                                       

   RECESSION WORRIES, fanned by Iraqi turmoil, hurt GOP
candidates the most.
   Oil-price fears fueled by Iraq's invasion will add to
voter concerns about a sluggish economy, falling house prices
and a possible severe downturn by fall elections. The party
in power usually gets the blame. "Combine a recession with
taxes and the S&amp;L crisis, and you've got a pretty deadly
situation" for the GOP, predicts Democratic political
consultant Paul Maslin.
   Most at risk: incumbent governors in states with soft
economies, including GOP governors in Rhode Island, Maine,
Florida, Nebraska and Iowa. A downturn would hurt GOP Sens.
Coats in Indiana and McConnell in Kentucky, and challenger
Schneider in Rhode Island. Democratic Sen. Baucus is
vulnerable in Montana, where the economy already is bad.
   Most economists think an actual recession will be avoided.
One bright spot: increased U.S. exports to Europe.
                                                                                                       

   HIGHER OIL PRICES from the Iraqi crisis "could hurt" the
movement toward raising taxes on energy as part of a budget
accord, says House Budget Committee Chairman Panetta. A House
Democratic leadership aide says energy taxes are still on the
table for now, but probably would be removed if oil prices
jump sharply.
                                                                                                       

   TAX RESISTANCE is linked to the S&amp;L scandal. "There's just
a sense of rage," says GOP Rep. Gingrich; voters ask if
Congress will "raise taxes for the savings &amp; loan bailout."
Democratic Rep. Williams says voters oppose taxes to pay for
"spending into infinity, and the biggest spending pit to
nowhere is the S&amp;L cleanup."
                                                                                                       

   MONEY FLOWS into Senate races. Texas Sen. Gramm leads the
way with $13.5 million. New Jersey Sen. Bradley is next at
$11.5 million. Others above $5 million: Sens. Helms, Simon,
Boschwitz, Kerry and Levin. GOP Senate hopefuls Rep. Martin
in Illinois and Rep. Tauke in Iowa raise more than $3 million
each, tops among challengers.
                                                                                                       

   FAMILY LEAVE heats up in the states, after Bush vetoes a
federal law. More than 12 states, including Illinois and
Pennsylvania, have bills pending to create or expand
job-protected leave. Democrats push leave "as one of the main
campaign issues" in the Illinois governor's race, says
Shelley Gates of Chicago's Women Employed.
                                                                                                       

   CLEAN AIR LEGISLATION is bogged down by delays and
disputes.
   More than two months after the Senate and House passed
bills, conferees have met just twice. Much of one session was
spent arguing over whether White House aide Roger Porter
could sit in. Environmentalists accuse Rep. Dingell and other
friends of industry of foot-dragging to increase their
leverage. Dingell denies delaying.
   William Fay, head of an industry coalition, says the
biggest threat to the bill "comes from the extremism of the
Senate." He contends senators push to combine the toughest
parts of both bills on such issues as industrial emissions of
toxic chemicals. The Sierra Club's Daniel Weiss grumbles
sarcastically that the process is "moving faster than a
speeding glacier."
   The White House raises its estimate of the annual cost to
industry of each bill to $25 billion by 2005, above the $21
billion Bush said he would accept.
                                                                                                       

   MINOR MEMOS: Illinois Rep. Annunzio tells Chicago magazine
he isn't worried about his district being redrawn because
"the only thing that the federal law on redistricting
provides is that the district be congruous and gregarious." .
. . HUD chief Kemp complains that at the Bohemian Grove
retreat in California recently he was given the Herbert
Hoover cabin. . . . Russian recycling: The hot new item for
sale in Moscow's main flea market is used McDonald's bags.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900803-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bear Stearns Cos.
   Profit Fell 30%
   In June Quarter
   ----
   By Robert J. Brennan and Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<CO>
   BSC
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Bear Stearns Cos. posted a 30% drop in net
income for its fiscal fourth quarter, capping a mixed
earnings season for Wall Street securities firms.
   The big securities firm, citing the cyclical downturn on
Wall Street, said net for the quarter ended June 30 was $33.5
million, or 32 cents a share, compared with $47.6 million, or
43 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue edged up to $640
million from $629.7 million. Many analysts had expected the
firm to earn between 40 cents and 43 cents for the quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Despite the results, however, Bear Stearns remains one of
the few securities darlings among financial-services
analysts.
   "I'm not table-pounding any of these stocks, but Bear is
the only one I have a buy on," says Larry Eckenfelder, an
analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. "It still has
good value and not a lot more downside."
   Yesterday, Bear Stearns shares closed at $12, down 62.5
cents, in composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Bear Stearns's results bring to a close an uneven period
for securities-firm earnings. For the first time in nine
months, securities firms as a group broke into the black in
the June quarter. But the results were mixed: Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co. surprised analysts with a jump in investment-banking
revenue, while Morgan Stanley Group Inc.'s shares have
dropped 18% since its disappointing earnings were released
last week.
   Bear Stearns's per-share results are adjusted for a 5%
stock dividend declared yesterday, to be distributed with the
regular quarterly cash dividend of 14 cents on Aug. 31.
   Commissions were a little softer than some analysts were
expecting; apparently an anticipated investment-banking deal
didn't close before the quarter ended, some analysts said.
Commission revenue for the quarter was down 22% to $77.9
million.
   Investment banking revenue rose 4.3%. An increase in
interest and dividend income was offset by an increase in
interest expense.
   For the year, Bear Stearns's net income fell 31% to $119.4
million, or $1.10 a share, down from $172.4 million, or $1.54
a share. Revenue was flat at $2.4 billion. Commission revenue
was down 2% but investment banking revenue dropped 17%.
   Strong performances in the areas of mortgage-backed
securities, government bond and stock trading helped the
fourth quarter, Bear Stearns said.
   In a statement, Chairman Alan C. Greenberg said "fiscal
1990, particularly the first six months, was a tough year for
the investment banking and brokerage industry." In light of
that, he said, "we are proud of our results for the quarter
and the year."
   Indeed, Mr. Greenberg showed good spirit and a touch of
humor about the results. "I have always heard that we are in
a cyclical business. I am eagerly awaiting the next upward
cycle," he said in the statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
