<HL>
   Mutual Funds:
   Benham to Offer
   Fund Transactions
   At Preset Prices
   ----
   By Jonathan Clements
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Benham Capital Management Group is hoping to lead the
mutual fund industry into the future by drawing on its
chairman's past.
   The chairman, James Benham, spent seven years as a Merrill
Lynch stockbroker before launching the Mountain View, Calif.,
fund company in 1972. As a broker, he found that limit orders
-- buy and sell orders that are triggered if a stock hits a
predetermined price -- were a favorite trading technique with
some customers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Now Mr. Benham is hoping limit orders will prove equally
popular with mutual fund investors. On Aug. 13, Benham, which
has $6.3 billion in assets, will launch its "open order"
service, which will allow investors to buy and sell mutual
fund shares at predetermined prices.
   Mr. Benham reckons the open order service will catch on
with investors in Benham's gold stock index fund and its
seven zero-coupon bond funds. "We probably have share prices
as volatile as anybody's," Mr. Benham says. "Some of those
{zero-coupon} funds move as much as 5% in one day." A
zero-coupon bond pays no interest, so the investor instead
can make gains from the narrowing of the bond's discount as
the redemption date approaches.
   Here is how the open order system will work. If a Benham
money market investor wants to buy, say, one of the fund
group's volatile zero-coupon bond funds, he will specify a
buy price that is lower than the bond fund's current share
price. If the bond fund falls to the specified price, money
is automatically switched out of the shareholder's money
market fund and into the bond fund.
   Benham also will allow shareholders in its gold and bond
funds to sell at predetermined prices that are above the
current fund share price. If the fund share price hits this
predetermined price, Benham will switch the shareholder's
money into one of its five money market funds.
   There will be no charge for switching among Benham's 21
no-load funds, though shareholders will be limited each year
to six round-trip exchanges for each fund. Mr. Benham says,
"We're not trying to turn people into traders."
   Mr. Benham had also hoped to introduce a variation on the
stop-loss order, which stock investors use to limit their
losses in the stock market. With a stop-loss order, a stock
position is automatically sold if the share price falls to a
specified level.
   But the Securities and Exchange Commission said it had
some concerns about stop-loss orders, so Mr. Benham decided
to seek approval only for the open order system. "In perhaps
six months or a year, we'll go back and apply for stop-loss
orders," he says.
   News of the innovation has received a tepid response from
others in the fund industry. "It is very innovative," says
Neal Litvack, a marketing vice president with Fidelity
Investments of Boston. "We'll be watching it very carefully.
But from a conceptual standpoint, it does run contrary to the
investment approach that we advocate to our investors, which
is a buy-and-hold approach."
   Kurt Brouwer, president of Brouwer &amp; Janachowski, a San
Francisco investment advisory firm, doubts that the idea will
catch on. "You're kind of encouraging people to trade, and
most fund groups don't want to do that," Mr. Brouwer says.
   "I don't think we're going to lose any shareholders over
this," says a spokesman for T. Rowe Price Associates,
Baltimore, who reckons the open order system will encourage
needless short-term trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0090
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900803-0090.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   It's a Real Jungle
   In Merc's Oil Pits
   On Invasion Day
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Far from the Middle East battle lines, the
front lines at the New York Mercantile Exchange's oil pits
got mighty rough yesterday.
   Traders, their arms flailing, bumped and bulldozed for
position as the closing bell capped one of the most volatile
days ever in the Merc's crude-oil pits.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Most traders, hoarse and sweaty, were in no mood to gab as
they sized up their trading positions.
   "Your throat hurts, your feet hurt -- you take a real
physical pounding," said George Gero, a 20-year veteran
commodity trader at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   When the dust settled, the September crude-oil contract
had jumped $1.57 a barrel, to $23.11, after leaping as high
as $23.80. That's the biggest one-day rise since April 1989,
and the highest closing price for crude oil since January.
   Oil traders thrive on gyrating prices, and there was
plenty of that yesterday as the markets reacted to Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait. There is fear that world oil supplies
will be disrupted; the two countries are among the biggest
oil producers. Together, Iraq and Kuwait represent more than
20% of the output of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
   But the Merc's rough-and-tumble local traders, who jump in
and out of the market trading for their own accounts, don't
keep their eyes glued to the newswires that flash above their
heads on electronic screens..
   "The best way to do it is to go with your instincts, to go
with the trading flow," says Lee Fader, a local trader at the
Merc. "You try to keep rumors out of your head," he says,
adding: "Rumors get you hurt."
   Some locals, for instance, trade on the basis of the price
spreads between oil contracts expiring months apart. Others
use byzantine technical charts to determine when they buy and
sell. Still others size up the feel of the trading pits for
clues, watching other traders' body language or facial
expressions to sense a change in price direction.
   Trading volume of 121,893 contracts at the Merc's
crude-oil ring fell far short of a record, however. That's
because many contracts quickly jumped the daily $1-a-barrel
limit; only the nearby September contract was free to move
more than $1. This means that many traders who had positions
in other contract months weren't able to wiggle out of them.
   On the elevator at the Merc, traders shook their heads and
sized up the damage. "I'm not a happy puppy," said one
glum-faced trader to his buddy. "Don't worry," chirped his
companion. "You're young."
   But oil wasn't the only hot spot in New York's commodity
pits yesterday. Gold prices, after surging more than $13
during the day, closed at $376.80 an ounce, up $3.50 at the
nearby Commodity Exchange here. Volume was a heavy 65,000
contracts.
   Many traders were betting that rising oil prices would
lead to higher inflation. And many people view gold as an
inflation hedge.
   "The first flight {by nervous investors} came into gold,"
says Prudential-Bache's Mr. Gero.
   What about tomorrow's trading? Look for somewhat lower
prices, some traders said, partly because oil and gold closed
well off their highs for the day. But no one was quite
willing to bet big on it yet.
   Says Mr. Fader, the local trader: "It's a crapshoot."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
