<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Mideast Conflict Raises Specter
   Of '70s-Style Economic Slowdown
   ----
   By Roger Lowenstein and John R. Dorfman
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST RTN GD
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Saddam Hussein's war is bad news on Wall
Street.
   Although oil and defense stocks rallied yesterday, the
market sank on fears that Iraq's invasion of Kuwait will lead
to sustained higher oil prices, dragging down broad swatches
of the economy as the oil shocks of the 1970s did.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts warned that the outlook for corporate earnings,
inflation and economic growth has darkened appreciably.
   "Fundamentally, it's not good for bonds. It's not good for
corporate earnings. And therefore, it's not good for stocks,"
says Steven Einhorn, the investment strategist at Goldman,
Sachs.
   According to Mr. Einhorn, only about 15% of the issues in
the Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index are energy-related and
could benefit from yesterday's news. For the other 85%, war
news was bad news.
   And Wall Street, which had seemed to be laughing off one
piece of bad news after another, was gloomy yesterday on the
general economic outlook. "The economy was teetering on a
cliff anyway," says Michael Harkins, an investor in New York
who isn't new to bearishness. "This could push it over" into
recession.
   Though the jury is out on that one, few dispute that
higher oil prices raise the risk of recession. Put simply,
because the U.S. is an importer, a rise in prices "siphons
purchasing power to external sources," says Richard Rippe,
economist at Dean Witter.
   And in some sense that goes deeper than the impact on oil
prices, Wall Street seems to fear that the invasion marked a
turning point.
   The invasion and higher oil prices, for instance, could
revive both the expectation and the reality of inflation,
worsen the U.S. trade deficit and make it tougher for
Congress to cut defense spending and arrive at a budget
agreement. And for all those reasons, the Federal Reserve may
be less apt to loosen credit.
   Call it a nest egg for less certain times: John Connolly,
chief investment strategist at Dean Witter, yesterday
recommended that the firm's clients move 20% of their
investment portfolios into cash.
   "This is not a passing event," Mr. Connolly says. "This is
not something that is going to go away this afternoon. It is
a basic change in oil politics in the Middle East."
   But while it never hurts to have some liquid assets, in
general, the notion that one should realign assets according
to the morning's headlines is highly suspect. So much, in
this case, depends on the actions of an Iraqi dictator who is
unlikely to tip off your broker before he changes course.
   And oil prices have had a history of doing the unexpected.
As Shad Rowe, an investor in Dallas, points out, "although
everybody is getting excited, that doesn't alter the fact
that oil is in oversupply."
   Iraq intends to cut back on supply. The question, as Mr.
Rowe frames it, is: "Is the Iraqi army more powerful than
supply and demand?"
   If the crisis is resolved quickly, says Stefan Abrams,
chief investment strategist at Kidder Peabody, "all we're
looking at is a moderate increase in the price of oil." That
would be disruptive, he says, but not catastrophic.
   However, Abby Joseph Cohen, U.S. strategist for Barclays
de Zoete Wedd, says the invasion comes at an especially bad
time for the stock market.
   "The way the market has been priced {relative to earnings
and interest rates}, you had to believe the bullish story" to
invest, she says. Wall Street, she notes, has been
forecasting earnings of about $25 a share for the S&amp;P 500 for
1990.
   But if oil prices rise, that figure will be tough to reach
-- it may have been out of reach anyway. Rising oil prices
thus make the stock market look even more dicey.
   "Until recently, the market put a positive spin on every
piece of news," Ms. Cohen says. But it is hard to put a
positive spin on Saddam Hussein.
   One area for which the invasion is bullish is defense. "It
does show that the world isn't quite the halcyon place that
some might have you believe," says Wolfgang H. Demisch, an
analyst with UBS Phillips &amp; Drew. Just maybe, then, Congress
will think twice before cutting back spending on conventional
weapons.
   And suppliers to the Middle East will probably find their
customers a bit more ready to do business. Raytheon is one
possible beneficiary; analysts say Raytheon is planning or is
in the process of selling its Patriot defense missile system
to Israel, Saudi Arabia and Italy. Raytheon's shares rose 2
3/4 yesterday to 60 3/4.
   General Dynamics, which is selling tanks to Saudi Arabia,
also could benefit from stepped-up tensions in the Middle
East, but analysts say the overall impact on the company is
likely to be small. The stock closed at 28 1/4, up 1 1/2.
   And as a result of the past year's lessening of tensions
in Europe, Congress and the U.S. public seem agreed that
defense spending should be cut back. Analysts doubt that the
invasion will be enough to deter Congress from that general
course.
   "Under Carter and Reagan, we had nine years of 20% annual
growth in {defense} procurement," says Judith Comeau of
Goldman Sachs. The U.S., therefore, has "an inventory of
aircraft, ships and electronics" that could be deployed in a
regional crisis, she says.
   "Playing" oil stocks is similarly chancy. Although oil and
oil-service, natural gas and other energy stocks rose
yesterday, that is old news as far as investors are
concerned.
   Stephen A. Smith, oil analyst with Bear Stearns, sees a
"tendency" toward higher oil prices. But Mr. Smith, and just
about every other oil analyst, was caught off guard by Iraq's
strike. Its next step is apt to be no less surprising.
   Plenty of stocks -- railroads, airlines and even companies
dependent on airline travel such as Walt Disney -- were
rocked yesterday.
   However, Michael Sherman, chief strategist for Shearson
Lehman Hutton, cautioned against making rapid portfolio
changes such as dumping airline stocks.
   One problem with that strategy, he says, is that airlines
are more dependent on the level of travel than just on the
price of oil.
   And more fundamentally, investors who sell on such widely
known bad news end up selling when everyone else is selling
-- usually the worst time to do it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0084
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900803-0084.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media -- Advertising:
   Wexler, High-Profile Lobbyist,
   Is Acquired by Hill &amp; Knowlton
   ----
   By Joanne Lipman
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS WPPGY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Hill &amp; Knowlton, the public relations giant that has made
a major push into lobbying, is trying to boost its Washington
presence by acquiring high-profile lobbyists Wexler,
Reynolds, Fuller, Harrison and Schule.
   The move plunges Hill &amp; Knowlton into grass-roots
lobbying, a particularly fashionable brand of
influence-peddling that is Wexler Reynolds's specialty.
Grass-roots lobbying basically involves organizing local
groups so that the lobbying firms' clients appear to have
widespread local support. Among Wexler Reynolds clients are
AMR's American Airlines, the Insurance Information Institute
and the Motion Picture Association.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The merger doesn't involve cash or stock changing hands;
rather, Wexler Reynolds's staff simply will join that of Hill
&amp; Knowlton, said Robert Dilenschneider, the PR firm's
chairman and chief executive officer. He said Wexler
Reynolds, with billings of about $7 million, will boost Hill
&amp; Knowlton's Washington office to over $30 million, making it
the second-largest office after New York.
   "They're excellent in some specialties, one of which is
coalition-building. We see that as the future," Mr.
Dilenschneider said.
   Wexler Reynolds's principals hail from the Nixon, Carter
and Reagan administrations. Principal Craig L. Fuller, who
had been chief of staff to then-Vice President George Bush,
becomes president and chief operating officer of Hill &amp;
Knowlton's public affairs unit. He will report to Robert
Gray, the unit's chairman.
   Mr. Gray, who forged his political ties while acting as
communications director for the 1980 Reagan-Bush campaign,
sold his own lobbying firm to Hill &amp; Knowlton in 1986.
   The acquisition comes as Hill &amp; Knowlton, a unit of
London-based WPP Group, is about to announce a major
reorganization. Today, the PR firm, the nation's
second-largest, expects to name Thomas E. Eidson, 46 years
old and currently president and chief operating officer of
U.S. operations, as president and chief executive of Hill &amp;
Knowlton International, a new unit responsible for operations
outside the U.S. He will be replaced by John D. Bergen, 47,
who had been executive vice president and head of the New
York office.
   The New York office, meanwhile, will be divided into three
different offices, headed by Peter Rae, 36; Kenneth Altman,
38; and Christopher P.A. Komisarjevsky, 45.
   Several executives outside the U.S. will also be
reshuffled, including David Wynne-Morgan, chairman of the
London office, who becomes chairman and chief executive of
European operations, succeeding Claudio Belli.
   Noting that the newly promoted executives, including Mr.
Fuller, are relatively young, Mr. Dilenschneider said, "We've
begun to put players in place who will have a run at running
the company over the next 10 years." At 46, though, Mr.
Dilenschneider isn't near retirement age himself.
   With the Wexler Reynolds affiliation, Hill &amp; Knowlton is
trying to reinforce its lobbying prowess. It isn't the only
PR firm to buy up Washington lobbyists; its sister WPP
company, Ogilvy &amp; Mather, has also been quite active,
acquiring, among others, Targeted Communications Corp., a
direct-mail firm, and a 30% stake in Charls E. Walker
Associates Inc. But Hill &amp; Knowlton is undoubtedly among the
most aggressive buyers.
   Already the company has built something of a lobbying
supermarket. It has traditional lobbyists who buttonhole
lawmakers. But it also has researchers, economists, political
analysts, publicists, graphic artists, speechwriters and
managers of campaign contributions. It even houses an
electronic broadcast studio, and produces radio and
television spots ranging from video news releases to
documentaries.
   The Wexler Reynolds merger gives Hill &amp; Knowlton even more
clout. Anne Wexler, a former Carter aide who founded the firm
10 years ago, is considered one of the most powerful
Democratic lobbyists in town. She will become vice chairman
of Hill &amp; Knowlton Public Affairs and chairman of the newly
named Wexler Group. Nancy Clark Reynolds, who had been close
to Nancy Reagan during the Reagan administration, will be
Wexler Group's vice chairman.
   Mr. Fuller said Wexler Reynolds decided on the Hill &amp;
Knowlton alliance after discussions with "three or four of
these large organizations." He said the 45-person firm is
merging in part because it's expanding the scope of its
business and working with some international clients that
could be helped by Hill &amp; Knowlton's 64 offices in 23
countries. The lobbying firm, for example, has been
representing American Airlines in its bid to get federal
approval to expand in Latin America, Europe and Japan.
American is also a Hill &amp; Knowlton client.
   Mr. Dilenschneider said that Wexler Reynolds had just one
client conflict with Hill &amp; Knowlton: Wexler Reynolds handled
Coke, which it had to give up because Hill &amp; Knowlton handles
Pepsi.
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   NEW ACCOUNT: Gates Energy Products, Gainesville, Fla.,
named Earle Palmer Brown, Atlanta, to handle its in-trial
battery account. Billings weren't disclosed.
</TEXT>
