</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Iraqi Invasion of Kuwait:
   B-2 Bomber's
   Supporters Win
   On Senate Floor
   ---
   Mideast Turmoil Buttresses
   Arguments That Keep
   Embattled Plane Alive
   ----
   By Andy Pasztor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP NOC
</CO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Seizing on the turmoil in the Middle East to
buttress their arguments, supporters of the B-2 Stealth
bomber won a narrow victory on the Senate floor to keep the
embattled plane alive.
   By defeating a pair of amendments to end or delay
production of additional radar-eluding B-2s, the Senate set
the stage for a historic test of wills with the House over
the kind of military forces the U.S. needs to cope with
Soviet nuclear threats and Third World crises in the late
1990s and beyond. The margin of victory was eight votes or
fewer in both instances.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In spite of the fact that saving the B-2 remains President
Bush's highest military priority, the House is almost certain
to reject additional purchases of the bat-shaped bomber when
it approves its version of the defense authorization bill in
September.
   Reflecting sharp erosion of bipartisan support even in the
Senate, lawmakers overwhelmingly voted to withhold any more
production funds until the Air Force and Northrop Corp., the
prime contractor on the B-2, present convincing new test
results showing that its performance in the air has matched
its billing.
   "This horse is heavy enough already," said Sen. Sam Nunn
(D., Ga.), adding that significant further delays will make
it "very, very difficult to ever sell it to the American
people."
   Still, yesterday's dramatic series of votes was a victory
for both President Bush and Sen. Nunn, chairman of the Armed
Services Committee. Sen. Nunn staked his reputation as the
Senate's leading voice on defense matters on the outcome of
the B-2 battle. Last year, only 29 senators voted to cut off
B-2 production. This time, 43 senators voted to halt
purchases and begin closing down the assembly line, while 56
opposed the amendment.
   Acknowledging that "the popular decision in the United
States today {would be} to cancel the B-2," Sen. James Exon
(D., Neb.), another outspoken supporter, urged the Senate to
salvage the "quantum leap forward" in technology.
   The lengthy debate originally was expected to focus on
arms-control issues, the B-2s huge price of more than $850
million a plane, and disputes about Soviet military
capabilities and intentions. Instead, Iraq's bloody invasion
of Kuwait altered the tone of the entire debate. Supporters
of the B-2, who clearly had been on the defensive before,
gained momentum and fresh ammunition by attacking Iraq's
moves and pointing out the B-2's capabilities to respond to
such an emergency.
   The unexpected Iraqi attack "reminded {lawmakers} there is
a lot of mischief in the world," Senate Minority Leader
Robert Dole (R., Kan.) said. "We ought to err on the side of
being prepared."
   Almost every lawmaker who joined in the debate -- from
staunch supporters of the B-2 to newly converted opponents
such as Sen. John Glenn (D., Ohio) -- tried to capitalize on
the Middle Eastern development to help make their case. Sen.
Glenn, a former astronaut and advocate of new aviation
technology, took the Senate floor to announce that after
weeks of "agonizing" he concluded that the B-2 would siphon
off badly needed funds from conventional weapons and military
personnel accounts. The Air Force, he said, simply hasn't
"been willing to address that {issue} head on," adding that
the B-2 "isn't what we need to go against the situation in
the Persian Gulf."
   All told, the Senate approved almost $2 billion for
procurement of two more B-2 bombers and at least that much
for continued research and testing during the fiscal year
starting Oct. 1. The Pentagon has spent about $27 billion for
15 planes already authorized or currently being built. The
total price is expected to be well over $65 billion if the
fleet of 75 B-2s proposed by the White House is built. Barely
a few months ago, the Pentagon insisted it needed 132 of the
planes to fulfill its nuclear-deterrent mission.
   In his spirited defense of the plane, Sen. Nunn argued
that terminating production would send U.S. arms-control
negotiators "back to the drawing board" and leave the U.S.
vulnerable to continued improvements in the Soviet's nuclear
arsenal. "All of us are suffering from sticker shock" with
the B-2, he acknowledged. But if Soviet advances eventually
force the U.S. to begin investing in a new network of
super-sophisticated air defenses, he said, "it will make the
. . . B-2 look like the biggest bargain we ever killed."
   The anti-B-2 amendment that garnered the most
votes-introduced by Sens. William Cohen (R., Maine) and
Patrick Leahy (D., Vt.) -- sought to withhold all new
production money until at least 1992, pending the outcome of
flight tests. "The biggest stealth characteristic of this
plane has been its mission," Sen. Leahy asserted, adding:
"Unfortunately, it's not stealth dollars." The amendment
failed on a 53-45 vote.
   B-2 supporters insisted that a one-year disruption in
production could be tantamount to killing the entire program,
by adding $4.7 billion to the already skyrocketing cost of
the B-2 and prompting layoffs of some assembly-line workers.
   In a speech to the Aspen Institute in Colorado, President
Bush echoed that sentiment. "To maintain clear and confident
strategic deterrence into the next century, we need the B-2.
. . . further delay will only increase cost." The president
also urged Congress to fund continued development of the
Midgetman and mobile MX missiles.
   Working late into the evening, the Senate also defeated an
amendment that would bar construction of an airbase in
Crotone, Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900803-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Iraqi Invasion of Kuwait:
   CIA Had Given Warning
   Of Iraq's Move on Kuwait
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- U.S. intelligence officials had been
sounding alarms in recent days about a possible Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait.
   Emphasizing that the Central Intelligence Agency wasn't
surprised by the Iraqi action, an agency spokesman said
yesterday, "We provided policy makers with very useful and
timely information on these events and we continue to do so."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Administration and congressional officials agree that the
CIA did its job. Since last week, President Bush had been
warned by intelligence analysts that what originally looked
like a military bluff was quickly turning into the kind of
troop deployment that could be used to invade Kuwait or even
Saudi Arabia.
   Central Intelligence Agency Director William Webster even
hand-delivered certain fresh details on the Iraqi buildup to
National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft. Among the
assessments he conveyed was a conclusion that, by this week,
President Saddam Hussein's force would be capable of
penetrating Kuwait or Saudi Arabia.
   The agency lacked hard evidence of an intent to invade,
intelligence officials say. But as the buildup grew, the CIA
became more alarmed, partly because Mr. Hussein is so
unpredictable, and partly because, unlike many other Arab
leaders, he has been known to carry out his threats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900803-0022
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900803-0022.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Bonds Fall as Iraq's Invasion of Kuwait Stirs Fears
   Of Rising Oil Prices and Higher Inflation Rate
   ----
   By Constance Mitchell and Stuart Drown
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   RJR FRE FNM EUROP JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Iraq's invasion of Kuwait sent bond investors
scrambling for cover yesterday on fears that war between the
two Middle East nations will cause oil prices -- and
inflation -- to soar.
   The sell-off started during overnight trading in Tokyo and
continued in London and New York. Traders said activity was
busiest in London, where dealers reported heavy selling by
investors from all around the world, including those in the
U.S., Britain, Saudi Arabia and Japan.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Even investors in smaller countries were big sellers. "We
were extremely busy in Singapore," said Lawrence Leuzzi, a
managing director at S.G. Warburg &amp; Co.
   The prospects of higher oil prices not only increase the
odds that inflation will accelerate, but could force the
Federal Reserve to change monetary policy.
   News that oil prices are rising, "is coming at the worst
possible time, when the economy is already extremely weak and
when there is a major effort underway to reduce the size of
the budget deficit," said Norman Robertson, chief economist
at Mellon Bank Corp. He said that rising oil prices will make
it difficult for the Federal Reserve to further reduce
interest rates. At the same time, high oil prices will drag
down already weak business activity.
   "If not recession, this certainly carries the threat of
stagflation, where oil prices rise and exacerbates inflation
and at the same time reduces the economic growth rate. It's a
very vicious brew here," said Mr. Robertson. The economist
estimates that if oil prices rise to $25 a barrel, the
nation's inflation could rise about 1/2 of a percentage point
to between 4.5% and 5%.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, September crude
settled at $23.11 a barrel, up $1.57 on the day. The contract
traded as high at $23.80.
   The yield curve steepened in reaction to yesterday's news,
as prices of short-term securities ended unchanged to
slightly lower while prices of long-term bonds were
clobbered.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond fell 1 1/4 point, a
loss of about $12.50 for a bond with a $1,000 face amount.
The issue's yield, which moves in the opposite direction of
its price, jumped to 8.45%.
   Two-year notes, on the other hand, fell less than 1/8
point to yield 7.88% while three-month bills ended unchanged
to yield 7.66%.
   Some traders detected signs of "flight-to-quality" buying
of short-term Treasury bills yesterday, but were surprised
there wasn't more of this, in view of the financial market's
reaction to the Iraqi invasion. Because U.S. Treasury bills
are considered the safest securities in the world, investors
often sell out of other securities and aggressively buy
Treasury bills when there is political or economic upheaval
in other parts of the world.
   But trading yesterday was dominated by investors making
"yield-curve trades," essentially selling long-term Treasurys
while buying short-term securities on expectations that these
securities will outperform the market in the coming weeks and
months.
   In the wake of the Iraqi invasion, economic data released
yesterday passed more-or-less unnoticed. Those reports were
the latest data on claims for unemployment and factory
orders. As trading quieted late yesterday afternoon, however,
the market began to focus on the July employment report due
this morning.
   The market is looking for the report -- the first official
indication of the economy during July -- to confirm signs of
marked economic deterioration.
   "The question is, if it is a good number, how high can the
market go, now that they've fallen like this," says one
trader.
   Economists surveyed by Dow Jones Capital Markets Report
estimate on average that nonfarm payrolls increased by 5,300,
or by 130,000 excluding layoffs of census workers.
Unemployment is seen rising 0.1% to 5.3% during July.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond ended at a price of
103 2/32, down from 104 8/32. The issue's yield climbed to
8.45% from 8.35%. Two-year notes were quoted at 100 6/32 to
yield 7.88% compared with 100 9/32 to yield 7.83%.
   Short-term rates were little changed. The discount rate on
three-month bills was unchanged at 7.43% for a
bond-equivalent yield of 7.66% while the rate on six-month
bills was modestly higher at 7.31% to yield 7.67%.
   The Treasury Department auctioned $4 billion of 44-day
cash management bills yesterday. The average rate was set at
7.60%.
   Here are details of the auction:
                                                                                                       

   Rates are determined by the difference between the
purchase price and face value. Thus, higher bidding narrows
the investor's return while lower bidding widens it.
                                                                                                       

               44-day Cash Management Notes
                                                                                                       

   Applications ............................ $28,376,000,000
   Accepted bids ...........................  $4,029,600,000
   Accepted at low price ...................             86%
   Average price (Rate) ....................  99.071 (7.60%)
   High price (Rate) .......................  99.072 (7.59%)
   Low price (Rate) ........................  99.071 (7.60%)
                                                                                                       

   Interest rate 7.78%. The notes are dated Aug. 7 and mature
Sept. 20, 1990.
                                                                                                       

   Corporate, Junk Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Junk bonds ended between 1/2 and 3/4 point lower. Trading
was limited, however, and junk-bond dealers said that in most
cases prices were simply quoted lower. Junk bonds are
speculative-grade issues that carry low ratings or no ratings
at all.
   Among the high-yield bonds that suffered losses were
pay-in-kind bonds of RJR Nabisco Inc., which staged a partial
rebound after falling more than two points earlier.
Pay-in-kind bonds pay interest in the form of more securities
instead of cash.
   RJR Nabisco 17 3/8% convertible pay-in-kind debentures
fell one point to 113 5/8 on the New York Stock Exchange.
RJR's 17% exchangeable pay-in-kind debentures finished one
point lower at 91 3/4.
   Despite yesterday's declines, First Boston Corp. said its
junk-bond index showed a positive return of 3.23% in the
month of July.
   Advancers outpaced decliners by more than four to one, and
the value of the First Boston high-yield index reached 149.45
in July, surpassing its July 1989 peak of 147.91.
   "This is the first time the market has recouped all the
losses from mid-1989 till February," said Sam DeRosa-Farag, a
high-yield analyst at First Boston.
   In addition, Mr. DeRosa-Farag pointed out that bonds,
which are trading at between 60 to 80 cents on the dollar,
are beginning to outperform bonds trading at par and above.
   Bonds in the 60-cents to 80-cents on the dollar range
produced positive returns of 4.6% in July compared with a
2.1% positive return generated by bonds trading at par and
above, said Mr. DeRosa-Farag.
   In the investment-grade market, prices of high-grade
corporate bonds ended between 3/4 point to one point lower.
                                                                                                       

   Municipal Securities
                                                                                                       

   Municipal bonds finished 1/4 to 1/2 point lower in calm
dealings.
   Despite the slight losses, traders said the supply
shortage in municipals continues to provide solid support and
foster bullish sentiment.
   Among actively traded secondary issues, the New Jersey
Turnpike Authority's 7.20% securities of 2018 finished 1/4
point lower at 99 1/2, pushing the yield up to 7.23% from
7.21% late Wednesday.
   In the new issue sector, the Pennsylvania Housing Finance
Authority's $80 million single-family mortgage revenue bonds
were priced by a PaineWebber Inc. group.
   The bonds, which are subject to the alternative minimum
tax, were priced at par to yield from 6.30% in 1994 to 7.65%
in 2023.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-, Asset-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-backed securities ended lower.
   Among actively traded issues:
   Government National Mortgage Association 8.5% securities
were down 13/32 at 95 17/32, and the 9.5% issues, at 100
12/32, were down 10/32.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. 9.5% issues were off 9/32
at 99 25/32, and Federal National Mortgage Association 9%
issues were down 11/32 at 97 31/32.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Iraq's overnight invasion of Kuwait caused global bond
prices to tumble.
   In West Germany, prices were sharply lower. But traders
said there has been little panic-selling. The trend much of
the day was set in the Bund futures pit in London.
   Bonn's 8.75% benchmark bond due 2000 fell 0.63 point to
100.32 to yield 8.69%.
   British government bonds, called gilts, ended with losses
of as much as 3/4 point, but they had been down by well over
a point at midday.
   Britain's benchmark 11.75% bond due 2003/2007 was quoted
late at 102 15/32, down 22/32 to yield 11.37%.
   In Tokyo, dealers said the market closely followed the
movement of the U.S. dollar, with yen bonds recovering from
their lows whenever the the dollar retreated from its highs.
   At the 3 p.m. JST close of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the
yield on Japan's benchmark No. 119 bond was 7.575%. The price
was down 0.34 point to 85.29.
</TEXT>
