<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   OIL PRICES SOARED and stock and bond markets tumbled
world-wide in response to Iraq's invasion of Kuwait. Crude
prices rose as much as $3.50 a barrel and some analysts
forecast a $30 price. Oil and defense stocks rallied but most
issues sank on fears that costly petroleum will drag down the
economy. The Dow Jones industrials fell 34.66 points, and
Tokyo stocks plunged. The dollar surged against the yen, but
gained little against the mark. Gold prices rose.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The jump so far in oil prices could cut the U.S. growth
rate almost in half, add a dime per gallon to the cost of
gasoline, and boost consumer prices 1% over the next year.
   ---
   Allianz agreed to buy the Fireman's Fund insurance
operations of Fund American for $1.1 billion, giving the
German firm a major position in the U.S. insurance market.
Trading on inside information about the deal may have
occurred as early as three days before the announcement.
   ---
   Factory orders fell a sharp 1.5% in June, providing more
evidence of a weakening manufacturing sector. Durable goods
were especially hurt.
   ---
   A troubled guarantor of student loans said the U.S.
blocked its attempts to stop accepting high-risk loans that
subsequently went bad.
   ---
   United Technologies' Pratt aircraft-engine unit plans to
cut 4,000 jobs, 11% of its work force, over three years. The
move is in response to spending reductions by the Pentagon.
   ---
   Sears and Montgomery Ward discussed "joint opportunities"
but ended the talks. Each affirmed its "intention to remain
independent."
   ---
   Chrysler expects its U.S. car market share to rise to
about 10% next year from 8.9% in 1990's first half.
                                                                                                       

   Ford may offer its workers iron-clad job security in
return for concessions to boost quality and productivity.
   ---
   The EC and the U.S. are talking quietly about expanding
cooperation in electronics research, in a new effort to
counter the Japanese.
   ---
   UAL's United Airlines should be picked to fly the highly
sought Chicago-Tokyo route, a Transportation Department
official recommended.
   ---
   Nynex proposes to test using digital radio transmission to
replace wire links between homes and Nynex sites. Such a
wireless system could save money as well as improve service.
   ---
   W.R. Grace named Vice Chairman J.R. Bolduc to be
president, giving him an apparent edge to succeed Chief
Executive J. Peter Grace.
   ---
   Akzo's second-quarter profit fell 24%. The Dutch chemical
company predicted a continuing earnings decline, and promised
more cost-cutting.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 253,090,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2864.60, off 34.66; transportation 1078.28, off 12.60;
utilities 212.09, off 0.81.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3473.95, off
34.34.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.13, off 0.39;
spot index 132.10, up 0.21.
   Dollar: 149.25 yen, up 2.07; 1.5915 marks, up 0.0030.
</TEXT>
